Triumph of the populist right in Austria, together they make up 29%
The anticipated elections to the Austrian parliament have brought, according to the first approximate results, an appreciable weakening of both parties of the current grand coalition and an expressive strengthening of the right-wing populist party.
Strong and special losses have been suffered by the Austrian People&#39;s Party (OVP), where the position of the current president, Wilhelm Molterer, is seriously shaken.
On the contrary, the leader of the Alliance for the Future of Austria (BZO), the head of the Carinthian state government, Jörg Haider, is preparing his triumphant return to national politics.
According to the approximate results, the Social Democracy (SPÖ) remains the strongest party in the country with 29.8 percent of the vote, thus losing 5.5 percent of the vote compared to the last elections in 2006. .
Worse still has finished the OVP losing 25.6 percent, almost nine percent of the vote.
They are the worst results, literally catastrophic, in the history of these two great Austrian parties since the war and especially for the popular ones that called these early elections.
Still in early July, when the OVP left the coalition, the popular had a considerable advantage in terms of preference over the SPO.
It is clear, however, that the voters chastised them for letting the government founder.
Already in the first reactions to the results, speculation was heard about the resignation of the party president and, until today, vice chancellor, Wilhelm Molterer.
Observers believe that this could already be achieved this Monday at the exceptional meeting of the party&#39;s presidency.
Such an evolution would obviously pave the way for the constant and closest starting point for the electoral results, that is, for the renewal of the grand coalition between SPO and OVP.
Given that the strengthening of both parties of the populist right - the Liberals (FPO) have won approximately 18 percent and the BZO, eleven percent of the vote - and that the Social Democrats at the same time expressed their fears that The same thing happened in 1999 when the popular groups negotiated with the populists (then the FPO was a unit, but in 2005 it broke up from the BZO) for a coalition government that led to a sanction by the European Union.
Haider is clearly committed to this evolution and has already announced that he is prepared to collaborate with any party and that he is already assuming his return to Vienna, to national politics.
Also the Green Party has managed to reach the parliament although it has lost slightly and dropped from third to fifth place among the Austrian political parties.
No other party has clearly exceeded the four percent limit and is therefore not part of parliament.
Armed combat: the MP3 player against the mobile.
We advise you how to choose
While almost every mobile plays MP3 files, no MP3 player manages to make calls.
What seems clear that it is better to buy only the phone.
Even so, there are enough reasons for man to acquire only the player.
The choice practically depends on the manner of its use and the requirement of the future owner.
It will probably be difficult for you to buy the latest record player to listen to the latest Maxim Turbulenc album on it.
On the other hand, this type of musical products such as LP records no longer come out, and in terms of their quality there is not a single objective reason to continue buying them.
If vinyl records of art rock, jazz or blues music are crowding your shelves, you are probably dreaming of at least this type of turntable.
This is the same with the music that is on the way, that is, the compressed, simplified music - the music in MP3.
And here there are price and quality categories.
For some it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on a player, the same as for a Pink Floyd lover who will hardly try the twenty-crown market headphones.
Two ends, between which there is enough space for each.
The choice is wide.
It also decides the battery life
Some of the best players do much more than just play music and even what most mobile phones don&#39;t.
No current device is as universal as the telephone.
Compared to the most basic functions such as making calls, sending messages, it can play music and video, record both, it has a better or worse photography device and it can even navigate.
And when we take into consideration the Smartphone and the PDA they will also have a small computer in their pocket.
This is a small miracle since no refrigerator knows how to cook a barbecue and no television can take pictures.
The universality of mobiles also brings us disadvantages.
The more functions you use on the mobile, the sooner the indicator on the screen will light up asking to be recharged.
And playing music is one of the biggest energy guzzlers.
Few are the mobiles that manage to play music for more than ten or twelve hours, most much less.
In this sense, music players (especially the simpler ones) clearly have higher performance.
Therefore, keep in mind that cheap mobiles will not play more than two hours.
If in addition to this, on top of that, you constantly call, get yourself, for more security, a charger for work - this also applies to the most expensive devices.
With the MP3 player you won&#39;t have this problem, because even the worst ones can last at least 9 hours of uninterrupted operation after charging.
Another problem occurs when recording music on the mobile.
Unfortunately, only a part of the devices have the universal USB connector and, furthermore, not all of them can be connected directly to the computer without special software.
Of course it is possible to record music directly on the memory card but only in some non-reducing drives can the small memory cards used in mobile phones be connected.
In the players, with some exception (iPod), no special software is necessary.
It is enough to fill the device with music through the USB of the computer.
Most mobiles and players create their own order in the music library according to the name of the artist, album title, genre or also according to the user&#39;s rating.
Some devices only display a directory tree structure similar to Windows Finder and some recognize both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with OS).
The player tries to serve, the mobile knows better
When choosing a specific piece of equipment, take an interest in the battery resistance, the memory capacity, the quality and type of sound output and, of course, the ease of handling.
If you mainly listen to music in the background and you are going to listen to it only for a while every day, like on the tram, then any mobile phone that reproduces it will suffice.
What practically any mobile truly achieves.
You should not even be interested in the format in which the mobile or the player reproduces the music.
MP3 is reproduced by everyone and, practically, almost all the music that reaches you will be in this format.
It is among the most widespread and except for it, the absolute majority of devices play music in WMA format.
The minuses include the AAC format (format used by the Apple company and its iPod).
The best mobile phones also make it possible, for example, to buy music online.
It is enough through the internet of the mobile to visit the competent pages of the operator (or any other service provider) and buy a song or an album.
This service could be by itself a compelling argument to acquire a mobile for music.
Unfortunately, the operators&#39; offer is miserable and most of them are limited only to the fleeting hits on the radio.
The prices are not the lowest either.
However, in general, it is assumed that precisely this way of selling music (whether via GSM, internet or wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always carry a mobile with them.
Whenever you feel like listening to something, you&#39;ll find your mobile in your pocket, while the MP3 player is forgotten at home.
However, it still depends if you always carry headphones with you or at least handsfree.
If not, you can use an integrated player that almost every mobile has even if it is at least an MP3 player.
Probably the biggest advantage for many music phones will be their price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than three thousand.
Between three and four thousand crowns you can already buy a good walkman.
Most of you will be limited by the absence of a classic headphone jack.
The best, even when it comes to the technical part, like phones equipped with a 3.5mm input. for a classic headset, they cost up to fifteen thousand.
Again, the advantage of the players is nothing other than their easy service.
The simplest players - by no means necessarily the cheapest (see our selection) - are really handled by anyone.
The minimal functions, its handling similar to the previous current cassettes or also to the record player is evident.
It does not represent a threat in the sense that by mistake we connect to the internet with the mobile and, consequently, a gigantic bill for data downloads.
Which device to decide
Even the cheapest mobiles (for example, the Vodafone 527) generally have a slot to change the memory card (type M2, micro SD, etc.).
Even with the purchase of a suitable card it will reach two thousand crowns.
However, be careful.
Basic models are normally only equipped with a 2 GB maximum capacity card.
Only the most expensive have 8 GB memory.
If you already have a mobile and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, take a look at Cowon, Creativ, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or Iriver.
Depending on the capacity (maximum 2 GB) it is not necessary to spend more than 1,100 crowns.
If you consider yourself one of the most demanding music lovers, take hold of the most specialized mobile-walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have independent keys for the MP3 which makes a service as comfortable as that of the same player.
The most specialized of all is Sony Ericsson, whose walkman line phones have almost identical use as a standalone MP3 player.
The same service and the same category in terms of price, over four thousand crowns, but with a greater memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and accumulator (normally 15 hours, with a maximum performance of up to 35 hours), the brand mentioned above brings you MP3 players.
The first virtual operator is already going to arrive, this year, in the Czech Republic.
Probably
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite developed and our operators offer almost all services like their Western European partners.
However, here we are still missing something - the virtual operator, which would force those to be cheaper.
It probably won&#39;t be long in coming.
That Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe, we have already written on mobil.cz.
The rest was also confirmed by the Czech Telecommunication Office (ČTÚ) which warned that the price of SMS messages in our country is one of the most expensive in the entire Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming charges, a paradoxical situation is probably reached - for some customers of Czech mobile operators sending SMS from abroad will be cheaper than if they send them from home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that really wants to fight.
This probably seems paradoxical to us, since we have three mobile networks and their high coverage is more than 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to lament that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
The Chairman of the Board of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ), Pavel Dvořák, has already stated that there is no longer a place in the Czech Republic for any other operator.
It is perhaps true that for a classic operator with its own network it no longer has many possibilities (for the rest, it would be very difficult to find a frequency).
However, there is still one possibility - the virtual operator.
Precisely the entry of the virtual operator in the mobile telephony market brought a notable drop in prices to which the classical operators also had to react.
At the same time, even before the entry of sharks like Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile into the UK market, similar voices were heard both there and here.
It was shown that there is a place for this type of operators and that they can be successful.
For the rest, there is no need to look too far for examples.
In February of this year we informed you about the premiere of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
Just after half a year, this operator managed to obtain more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the neighboring country.
On the other hand, behind Mobilking is the Penta group which, apart from that, in the Czech Republic is the owner of U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators lies in the possibility of concentrating on many more specific target groups.
Furthermore, in order for them to function effectively, they need far fewer clients than a classic operator.
They do not carry with them relatively large expenses in construction, operation and maintenance of the network.
In the world, these types of virtual operators are usually low-cost - they offer cheap calls and SMS messages, which, however, is often offset by offering more adjusted services.
Thus, for example, Tesco Mobile in Great Britain offers SMS at least half as cheap as the competition.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, the commitment to a non-trivial target group can also be a good blow.
This operator is specifically addressed to man.
&quot;The right man chooses Mobilking - it&#39;s the operator you like and trust,&quot; says David Seibert, CEO of the Mobile Entertainment Company, which runs this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say if a similar concept like the one in Poland could catch on in our country.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav Čepický doubts this: &quot;The Czech market is relatively small to access the segments on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, from the point of view of the supply of services, it is relatively saturated&quot;
In the Czech Republic there are no chances, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there will be a virtual operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
&quot;We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, however, in the Czech Republic it does not look too hopeful.
Rather, it is about the launch of Mobilking in other countries in our region,&quot; Jana Studničková, spokeswoman for the Penta financial group, told mobil.cz in a telephone conversation.
He indirectly assured that the current mobile phone operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not inclined to this idea.
Rather the opposite, they try to do everything possible so that no potential competition arises.
Interest in the launch of a mobile virtual operator is already shown by the GTS Novera group that would like to take a step further to become a real competition for Telefónica O2 in the field of business customers.
&quot;We have a great interest in it, to be able to offer our clients not only fixed telephony services but also mobile telephony.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly encountered this possibility with all Czech mobile phone operators.
With some of them we have managed to make progress in the meetings,&quot; said group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
So perhaps better times are flashing.
It seems that, due to unofficial information, the first official operator would possibly have to arrive by the end of the year.
But for now his appearance is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
&quot;At the moment we believe that the situation is ideal for the emergence of a virtual operator on the Czech market.
The Czech market compared to others is a very specific market.
So far no one has approached us with any complex and serious project in this field,&quot; Vlastimil Sršeň, spokesman for Telefónica O2, told mobil.cz.
Other operators refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová, in exceptional agreement with O2&#39;s opinion, adds: &quot;Until today we have not registered any viable commercial project that, bilaterally profitable, can continue to be developed.&quot;
And he adds: &quot;In the T-Mobile network it will be difficult to find a virtual operator until the end of the year.
At this moment we should already have a specific contract on the table that would be possible to study in such a short horizon&quot;
Vodafone directs its attention rather to compliance with the requirements of a 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický adds: &quot;We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and this in terms of cost sharing and infrastructure.
We precisely consider it as the greatest contribution from the point of view of customers.
Vodafone&#39;s main strategy in this field lies in the partner with whom to establish a shared network for fast mobile internet.&quot;
Responsible offices - with the operators hand in glove
The progress of mobile operators can be easily understood, but the entry of another operator would mean increased competition, which would lead to lower prices and with it, lower profits.
So why facilitate entry to the competition?
When operators want to achieve something, they are capable of pulling the same rope, proof of this is the grab when U:fon emerged.
Perhaps the greatest pressure on ČTÚ was at the time of the entry of U:fon by the T-Mobile company.
This is confirmed by the public information accessible on the ČTÚ web pages.
But precisely now U:fon serves as an argument for why not accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová adds to this: &quot;In addition, not long ago the competitive environment in the mobile phone market was opened up to a fourth operator.
As far as the nature of the mobile phone market in the Czech Republic is concerned, it is natural that the entry of another player into the market would place great demands on it and, above all, on its services.&quot;
This is why this access to mobile operators is extremely discouraging due to the utter disinterest of the Czech regulatory body.
This is not only the position of the ČTU, which unfortunately has no competence to intervene in commercial tenders, unlike Great Britain and other developed countries.
This belongs purely to the Office for the Protection of Commercial Tenders (ÚOHS).
However, it expressed its typical position on this issue.
&quot;The entry of a virtual operator to the mobile telephony market would be possible after an agreement was closed on the rental of the necessary infrastructure between a mobile telephony operator and a virtual operator.
Until today, no agreement has been closed since the offer of the potential interested parties was rather not interesting enough for the classic operators&quot;, added Kristián Chalupa, from the ÚOHS Department of Foreign Relations, to our question.
These statements formulated do not surprise the representatives of the operators.
For offices that must represent the interests of consumers, this is more than just a consideration, apart from that they must ensure that no one takes advantage of their position in the market.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: &quot;Abroad, where virtual operators function normally, we can see that their entry into the market contributed to lower prices for mobile phone services&quot;
Obviously, the pressure regarding the correct functioning of the market means and the drop in prices are not within the interest of the ÚOHS.
What is really dramatically shocking in this whole case lies in the dissonant reactions that result from the three mobile operators.
The question of whether it really is a coincidence, offers itself.
It is the same as with the price of gasoline at gas stations because it is clear that it is the work of chance and a hard fight for competition.
&quot;The Office in this sense has not found signs of unfair competition and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position, therefore they do not have a corresponding increase in responsibility in their actions in the market.
The necessary tools to open the mobile telephony market to virtual operators, rather, are lacking, as are the telecommunications regulators,&quot; Chalupa added to his response.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many points of contention.
Obviously there is an analysis of relevant markets prepared by the ČTÚ according to which telecommunications are from the point of view of commercial bidding a single market.
In this type of market naturally none of the Czech operators have a dominant position.
However, some of the legal experts offer another view - for a virtual operator to emerge, the agreement with the network administrator is always necessary.
And the mobile phone operator - with all its logic - has a monopoly on its network.
Therefore, in a specific segment it must necessarily be dominant.
And if this argument is not accepted, at least for ÚOHS the fact that three mobile operators are rising remarkably in a similar way should represent a warning.
The current complaints from interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that in all negotiations with the operators they run up against many similar impediments.
Placing the responsibility on the ČTÚ is a fairly common trick in the field of telecommunications from which the ÚOHS washes its hands in this whole matter.
We have already met him in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, a short time ago a new amendment to the telecommunications law was presented for the extension of the ČTÚ&#39;s competence in the field of commercial tenders, which was not carried out, even though a number of specialists promised that the situation would improve.
The representatives of ÚOHS should be fully aware of this, but it is clear that their interests lie elsewhere.
Everything goes well, when no one is looking
At the same time, it inadvertently continues to function as a pseudo-virtual operator, of which there are already quite a few in the Czech mobile phone networks.
They are companies that set their own prices for mobile phone services which, however, only part of them are public.
Normally these are companies that are dedicated to multilevel marketing.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
Normally only a select few get the price list from these companies.
The magic is that the company, with respect to the operator, acts as a classic business client of the same, ordering a large number of SIM cards.
As a special customer you will then receive special prices and other offers.
The problem is that the commercial conditions in all Czech mobile phone operators prohibit this type of resale.
&quot;If cases such as the ones you cite were discovered, one could speak of a violation of the contract conditions that could lead to the end of the collaboration with the given company&quot;, answered Martina Kemrová when asked about this problem.
But it is highly unlikely that such activity by mobile phone operators would not reach responsible people.
Precisely in the case of the three companies mentioned, it can be thousands of customers.
None of the operators is against this procedure.
With the activities of these companies they make not inconsiderable profits and, at the same time - unlike the real virtual operators - they in no way threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns us of possible problems: &quot;The law allows such speculation, however, the services of this company are used by only a negligible percentage of customers.
These, in addition, must accept that the SIM card of their telephone is not in their name, so they cannot absolutely have it as a normal client of the operators.&quot;
This is precisely what should seem to the ČTÚ minimally strange.
In addition, a new question for the ÚOHS appears.
If mobile phone operators squint in this type of procedure, why do they block the entry of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that the ÚOHS has sufficient competence to discover this type of activity and if it is not going to want to, it should not be satisfied with the explanations of the operators that they have no idea of this story and that their commercial conditions do not allow it. allow.
When will we stop being the most expensive
As was already made clear in the text, the entry of the virtual operator in the mobile telephony market brought a significant decrease in the prices of services.
At the same time, in practically all the countries where the virtual operator emerged, the classic operators more or less tried to protect themselves from this irruption.
The arguments used by these were practically all identical - too small, a market eventually too saturated, problems with the quality of the service, etc.
In the most advanced countries, however, at this time the regulatory bodies have intervened and in none of the cases did they defend the operators but rather their customers.
Either through formal measures or informal pressure, they managed to bring about the first virtual operator and with it others began to emerge.
Unfortunately, the Czech Regulatory Body passes this whole case like a burning nail.
From our experience we cannot fail to be impressed that the confusion of attributions in these cases suits them.
But let&#39;s not despair.
If this behind-the-scenes information is correct and the virtual operator really comes to these lands, then the Czech mobile phone market will probably start moving again.
If any of the operators allows a virtual mobile phone operator to enter, it will be difficult for the ÚOHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And perhaps we will stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
choose the best
Listen to all four performances of the new version of the Czech official anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek presented the new official recording of the anthem Where, my home, on the occasion of the official Czech celebration day.
The new anthem was recorded by the National Theater orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available - two versions that are Solos, one for a male voice and another for a female voice, another with Choir and another instrumental.
Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka are in charge of singing.
The authors of the anthem arrangements are Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
On the iHNed.cz server you can listen to all four versions.
Bělohlávek considers this national Czech song one of the most beautiful hymns.
Czech Radio already said before that it intentionally chose for the solos singers with representatively young voices that are more expressive and popular.
&quot;From the beginning I have tried with both of them and later, also, with the Choir that they pay attention to the diction so that the text is well understood, so that it has consonance&quot;, he commented.
The Czech official anthem celebrates its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Where, my Home was played for the first time in 1834 on the stage of the Estates Theater in the original Czech play Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl and arranged to music by František Škroup.
It gained popularity and people embraced it.
The first verse of the song after the rise of Czechoslovakia in 1918 naturally became a part of the official anthem.
One of the seven official symbols remained even after the rise of the independent Czech Republic.
