On Wednesday, October 1, 2008, the history of the Prague Transport Company is written as the date when the first passengers entered the metro, tram and bus with an electronic voucher in their pockets instead of a ticket. of paper.
This can be purchased right now by almost one hundred thousand people who have the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can buy the 30-day, 90-day and annual pass (this will be valid from January 1, 2009) and simultaneously charge it to their chip card at the infocenters and posts of the transport company in the stations of the Metro, Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
Vouchers can already be bought since yesterday on the Internet on the pages of the transport company, www.dpp.cz.
The service, until the afternoon, was used by more than four hundred people.
Those who start using the internet as a form of commerce can definitely start to forget about the ticket booths in subway stations, where until now they had to regularly queue up to get a normal ticket.
The voucher is purchased online, and the Opencard card is recharged at one of the thirteen branches of the Municipal Library.
&quot;In these places there is a window with trained personnel available to passengers who help those interested with the purchase online and also with the recharge of the voucher purchased on their card,&quot; said the spokesman for the project, Martin Opatrný.
Apart from the library, it will also be possible to reload the electronic voucher on the Opencard in the automatic vending machines found in some subway lobbies.
How are these vending machines?
They are red, reminiscent of a ticket-slicing machine, and travelers have probably already noticed them at the Roztyly, Budějovická, IP Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská metro stations.
&quot;Now there are five in the city but by the end of the year there should be eighty,&quot; Opatrný completed.
The bonus is controlled by the machine instead of the driver
The use of the machine, which will start working tomorrow, is simple.
It is enough to insert the Opencard chip card into it and the previously paid bonus will be charged only to it.
Electronic vouchers from tomorrow are valid not only in the capital but also in its surroundings.
That is, on the ring trains and bus lines from numbers 300 to 499 that are mainly used by the inhabitants of the central Bohemian towns.
&quot;In the trains attached to the integrated transport of Prague there are conductors equipped with a reader card that will help to confirm the validity of the time and the zone of the voucher&quot;, thus explained the control of the tickets, Filip Drápal of the organization Ropid that establishes the schedules of public transport in Prague.
The ring buses have their reader cards mounted in the driver&#39;s ticket office.
When entering, it is necessary not only to show the card to the driver, but it is also necessary to accompany him with the Opencard in the place designated for it on the Cashier&#39;s side.
With this, the driver controls the validity of the voucher.
&quot;If the passenger needs to verify the validity of the vouchers, there is nothing easier than asking the driver for this information,&quot; Drápal completed.
Passengers who do not travel on the ring buses and do not remember when the voucher expires can go to the vending machines where the cards are recharged.
Here, on the screen of the machine, they will be shown the information about the validity of their document.
The Southeast wanted to be part of the US in a referendum
Sudeten Germans asked in 1945 that Fumaba be part of the United States.
This is what is extracted from the letter that is kept in the collection of the Scientific Library of South Bohemia.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want to at least live under the patronage of the United States of America.
It was with this wish that some groups of Sudeten Germans presumably turned to the US president in 1945.
It results from the letters that are kept in a private archive and that today are kept in the collection of the South Bohemian Science Library.
The Germans from Český Krumlov request in a letter to the American president not to allow the return of the &quot;Šumava land&quot; - occupied by Hitler on the basis of the Munich Pact - back to Czechoslovakia.
&quot;We have correctly understood the situation and we really want your word that the American units are coming to German lands not as oppressors or enemies but as liberators&quot; is written in the letter, signed with &quot;the people who bear the fate of Šumava in your heart&quot;.
In view of the fact that the union of Czechoslovakia with the South-East Germans presumably supposes - according to these the Czech national character - a hope only in brutality, inconsideration, misunderstanding, pressure and slavery, the authors ask in the letter to the American president to take office for today and forever to Šumava under a protectorate.
&quot;We cannot believe that without considering the opinion of four million inhabitants, he would hand us over to a foreign state that oppresses and rejects minorities and that in no way collaborates with the victory of the allies,&quot; the letter writes.
The reason why the authors cannot sign is presumably the fear of reprisals from the &quot;Czech oppressors&quot;.
If the US president presumably doubts this idea of the šumavian Germans, it would be enough to organize a referendum in the šumavian lands on whether its inhabitants want to be part of the US or live under its patronage.
Despite the fact that the text of the letter, with our current knowledge of post-war history, may sound a bit childish to us, according to some specialists it accurately depicts the expectations of the South-East Germans of that time.
Although the Czech Germans must have sensed that it was going to be about their expulsion from the republic, only a few admitted this possibility.
Some hoped that the United States and Great Britain would negotiate for the Sudetenland some clear form of autonomy.
Others believed that they will stay in Czechoslovakia.
This is even confirmed by the Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in České Budějovice.
He was in the war, as a German from Budějovice, enlisted in the Baltic Navy.
When he was seized by the British at the end of the war and placed in the Holstein prison camp, dozens of Germans came to him to be taught Czech.
&quot;They thought that when they came home, the Czech would come in handy,&quot; Chalupa said.
According to him, none of the German prisoners who lived in Czechoslovakia before the war counted on the fact that they would be removed from the Republic on the basis of the Benes Decrees.
