rats have feelings too
It is said that a rat or a cockroach, feeling danger, flees, why is it also afraid?
Joseph Le Doux, the scientist in the field of neurology is convinced that many animals also have feelings.
How can you control if they, behaving in the same way as us, feel the same?
In an Internet magazine called &quot;Edge&quot; for many years the contributions of famous scientists have been published.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series the chosen answers to the question What do you think is true without being able to prove it?
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness that I or someone else could not prove so far, although we can&#39;t even prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case at least we can expect it because all human brains have the same fundamental configuration.
But as soon as we turn to other species and include the questions about sensation and consciousness in general, we enter the unknown realm because the hardware doesn&#39;t match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same as other animals: it plays dead, flees, or attacks.
People behave in a similar way, from which some scientists draw conclusions about comparable subjective experience.
Naturally I don&#39;t think so.
Two aspects of brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to that of animals.
First, they almost always include the circuits associated with human consciousness from the lateral prefrontal lobe of the cerebral cortex (because of their involvement in short memory and executive functions that direct behavior).
This broad part is much more developed in the case of people than in other primates, and seems to be entirely lacking in other creatures.
Taking into account at least those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal lobe of the cerebral cortex, including knowledge about who we are and the ability to plan and decide, there is reason to suppose that even humans differ from other primates. .
Another peculiarity is found in the linguistic nature of man: Since most of his experience is linked with language, this often means that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals can be excluded.
But even if consciousness would not depend on language, it would influence it in such a way that the consciousness of animals, created however, would in many cases differ from most of our states of consciousness.
That is why it is difficult to explain how the consciousness of other animals works.
If that, as something interesting and subjective, cannot be measured because it has special hardware, nor can it be analyzed through our experiences, then your research presents us with big problems.
Most of my interventions are concerned with the content of conscious experience, but at the same time there is also another aspect of consciousness that should be easier for scientific investigations.
Consciousness processes in animals could be investigated without taking their contents into account, and that is what happens during studies of short-term memory in primates, especially in the example of visualization.
But with this approach followed by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, the essential goes more to the neutral correlates of consciousness than to the causal mechanisms: The two may or may not be similar.
Interestingly, this approach highlights the importance of the prefrontal lobe of the cerebral cortex for visualization training.
And what results from that for the sensations?
I owe it to the fact that in the emotional system a part of the brain that is responsible for that is activated, the same thing that happens with fear.
What we describe as fear is therefore a state of mind we are in when brain activity takes up space in the defense system (or its consequences, such as body reactions).
Seen from this point of view, the sensations are very fixed to part of the cerebral cortex, which distinguishes primates and especially man.
From the point of view of linguistic nature, classifications of fine sensations follow because we can differentiate and classify states with the help of words and grammar in order to describe the states of others besides ourselves.
For example, Antonio Damasco, on the contrary, thinks that sensations derive from the simple activities of the parts of the cerebral cortex responsible for bodily feelings and the brainstem, Jaak Pankseep thinks the same, but focuses more on the brainstem. brain.
Since this network has not changed much during human evolution, it can absolutely refer to different types and their sensations.
For theoretical reasons I can&#39;t go against that, but I consider it unlikely.
Pakseep argues that what rats and men feel as fear, possibly that is felt in two cases as well: But how can one control if rats and men behaving in a similar way feel the same?
Seeing the danger, a cockroach flees, because it is afraid?
I am of the opinion that similarity of behavior does not yet prove similarity of experience.
It is true that the neuronal comparison helps: rats and men have similar brain stems, cockroaches, on the other hand, do not have at least one brain.
Is it the brainstem that is responsible for sensations?
Even if it is possible to test it for men: How can you test it in case of rats?
I think rats and other mammals, possibly also cockroaches (who knows?), have sensations.
But I don&#39;t know how you can prove it.
I prefer to investigate emotional behavior of rats than emotional sensations because their sensations are supposedly fundamentally different from ours (because human consciousness is concerned with special circuitry and language).
In any case, progress in the field of neurology is expected here as long as the same is measured in rats and men.
Since I do not investigate the language and consciousness of rats, as well as sensations, I do not know if they exist.
It can be said that I don&#39;t see beyond my nose, but I prefer to move forward than to work permanently without results.
Well, I&#39;m a practical emotionalist.
