In a city apart, pride and proof of life of color
Hidden by the sprawling Orlando-themed park, a few miles from the bright, noisy, colossal city, lies a sleepy town, where the pride and intricacies of the African-American experience remain all too evident.
Eatonville, the country&#39;s first incorporated all-black city and the childhood home of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as simple as she described it in 1935: &quot;the city of five lakes, three croquet lawns, 300 men of color, 300 good swimmers, many guavas, two schools and not a jail.&quot;
Now it is a place of pilgrimage.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have come to the annual Zora! Fair in Eatonville to pay homage to Mrs. Hurston, the most famous writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
And yet, in many ways, the city she described – also making it a tourist stopover by including it in the Federal Writers&#39; Project&#39;s depression-season travel guide to Florida – remains a place apart. .
The city remains independent, dignified, and private as it was in the 1930s, when Ms. Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida were often resistant to sharing their true ideas with the white man, who &quot;knows so little about us and He doesn&#39;t know what he&#39;s missing.&quot;
Even now, in the year that a black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, has called attention to starting a dialogue on the issue of race, many remain wary of the outsider.
&quot;We&#39;re very cautious about the way our story is told,&quot; said Jones Hortense, 59, a lifelong resident and member of the city&#39;s oldest church.
&quot;It has to be correct.&quot;
Eatonville has always been defined as a paradox of triumph and struggle.
It is at the same time a historical model of black affirmation and a community of almost 2,400 people who live under a level of poverty twice the national average.
It&#39;s a literary hub, but also a repaired example of the rural culture of the black South - sometimes scorned, other times praised - that was born out of slavery in America.
No wonder, if those who reside here are both proud and reserved.
And the concern for Eatonville&#39;s image really started with Zora, since no one here calls her Mrs. Hurston.
She introduced her hometown to the world through her insightful dialect books like &quot;Mules and Men&quot; (1935) and &quot;Their Eyes Were Watching God&quot; (1937).
Five paragraphs in the Florida Guide transformed the city, just off Route 17, a highway that runs through central Florida often forgotten in black history and human drama.
Concrete-faced in both life and literature, Ms. Hurston led her readers into the store owned by Eatonville&#39;s first mayor, Joe Clarke, and later into more private areas.
&quot;Off the road on the left,&quot; he wrote, &quot;is the modern brown public school with its white trim, its well-kept gardens and playgrounds, tended by Howard Miller, as he can barely read and write.&quot;
She also mentions the Widow Dash&#39;s new husband and writes that Glenn Lee &quot;sells drinks of all kinds and anything goes with transitional rooms.&quot;
Thus, in just a few hundred words, Ms. Hurston links Eatonville to home rule, but also to illiteracy, remarriage and sex.
Obviously this Fodor did not.
In fact, not everyone appreciated the portrait.
&quot;Zora described it like it was,&quot; said Ella Dinkins, 90, one of the Johnson girls Ms. Hurston immortalized by quoting men who went around singing colorless songs about her beauty.
He added: &quot;Some people didn&#39;t like that.&quot;
Ms. Hurston is still remembered here as a vivacious eccentric who returned frequently after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Franklin Augusto, 77 years old, remembers that when Mrs. Hurston arrived in the city, she did so unannounced in a large Chevrolet, smoking and wearing pants in a city that even today prides itself on dressing with dignity.
Most of the residents were entranced, Mr. Franklin said, while many laughed sarcastically.
&quot;People were always so happy to see Zora,&quot; continues Mr. Franklin.
But, he adds, rocking in his chair in a backyard overlooking Sabelia Lake, where Mrs. Hurston was likely baptized, &quot;she never stayed very long.&quot;
When Mrs. Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were no longer in print.
Like most of the world, Eatonville also seemed to have forgotten about her.
Although she was a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes, and the only woman of color at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an anonymous grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she had been living.
In Eatonville, there were no grand memorial ceremonies, no grand public readings.
&quot;I don&#39;t think her contribution to the world or her heritage was understood,&quot; said Valerie Boyd, author of &quot;Wrapped in Rainbows,&quot; a biography of Ms. Hurston published in 2003.
A certain turn came in the &#39;80s.
Orange County officials wanted to put a five-lane highway through the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the main two-lane street in the working community.
The expansion of the Orlando area had already pushed Interstate 4 through the western edge of the city.
The proposal came at a time when Eatonville was recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Forced integration, among other things, had ended his relatively idyllic isolation from the community.
In the 1950s, the fight for racial mixing brought hatred closer to the community.
&quot;During that season, a bunch of white kids, they were going around town throwing oranges and everything at the people who were sitting next to them,&quot; Mr. Franklin said.
&quot;They also killed a girl, once.
They threw him against a watermelon from the car.&quot;
In a 1955 letter to Mrs. Hurston, he wrote to The Orlando Sentinel, criticizing the forced integration by the Supreme Court that, in Brown v. Board of Education &quot;insulted rather than honored my race.&quot;
A Residents say today that the desegregation of schools, positive in some ways, had weakened Eatonville&#39;s cohesion and undermined the confidence of its youth.
&quot;Black children were used to being hugged - I remember this - it was customary to hug the teacher in the morning and at night,&quot; said NY Nathiri, the daughter of Ella Dinkins and executive director of Preserve the Eatonville Community, a non-profit organization. profit.
This lasted, he added, until the teachers and students did not come from the same place.
&quot;I wasn&#39;t hugging your teacher because he was white - there&#39;s a cultural gap there,&quot; said Ms Nathiri.
Civil rights, however, helped create the space for many more Zora Neale Hurstons – black writers, actors, and artists who stepped over prejudice, just as she did, with buoyant confidence and lines like: &quot; How can anyone deny himself the pleasure of my company!
I don&#39;t understand.&quot;
In 1975, writer Alice Walker went to Mrs. Hurston&#39;s anonymous grave and began fighting to resurrect her reputation.
Five years later, an acclaimed biography of Mrs. Hurston by Robert E. Hemenway appeared in bookstores, reintroducing her into American canons.
The highway project came just as Eatonville&#39;s most famous daughter was once again in the spotlight.
And this time, Mrs. Hurston&#39;s old neighbors saw her as a savior.
In 1988, the community began planning a fair for Mrs. Hurston to show what the county could ruin with that road.
Thousands of fans turned up for the inaugural event two years later, and every January, many return for the celebration.
After several years, the county has abandoned its highway proposal.
&quot;The resurrected idea of the five-lane highway would have been to put in what you would call curvature speed, a real civic pride,&quot; said Ms Nathiri.
Ms. Boyd put it more simply: &quot;Zora saved Eatonville.&quot;
The victory over the highway project has helped change the image of the city itself.
Out-of-towners like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who began coming to the church here in 1993, began showing up in large numbers, and residents began revisiting the past.
