Second round for the best seller from Honda
In the month of November Honda will begin marketing the second generation of the Jazz.
If its predecessor already had ample room, this new minivan has an even larger interior space.
Added to all this are refined mechanics, which increase driving comfort and save more fuel.
Evolution versus revolution.
This is the second generation of the Honda Jazz.
Although aesthetically the new Jazz presents a very similar line to the model that follows, the changes introduced in this minivan are numerous.
Among others, it is worth noting an innovative design, a new platform, larger dimensions and new mechanics.
However, before analyzing the new model, it should be noted that this new Jazz comes six years after the first generation was introduced to the market.
Therefore, a first observation is that Honda has renewed this model in a shorter period than that used by other manufacturers.
Although in Europe the Jazz is less known, in other markets this model is a sales phenomenon.
This is the case of Japan, a country where the Jazz has been the most sold car in 2002 and also during this 2008.
Precisely in Japan, close to one million units of the Jazz have been sold since its launch.
The second market has been that of the Old Continent, with around half a million units in six years.
However, Honda claims that this new Jazz will increase sales within the segment.
Thus, while in 2007 the Japanese firm sold a total of 83,000 units of the Jazz, in 2009 estimates point to 100,000 cars, which would mean a growth of 17% in the European market.
Regarding the Spanish market, Honda has sold a total of 8,000 units of the Jazz since 2002, representing 6.7% of all Honda sales in Spain.
As for the new generation, those responsible for the Spanish subsidiary expect to sell 2,000 units of the Jazz in a full year.
Precisely the arrival of the new Jazz will allow Honda to greatly alleviate the decline in sales in Spain.
In fact, those responsible for the brand expect to end the year with a total of 22,000 units sold, which is 4,000 less than in 2007, a drop of 16%.
Despite this increase in sales, Honda has increased its market share in Spain, reaching 1.8%, compared to 1.6% last year.
Likewise, the Japanese firm expects to achieve 2% in 2010.
To achieve this quota, Honda trusts the arrival of another new model.
This is the Insight, a five-door hybrid with a compact size - 4.37 meters in length - of which the Japanese company expects to sell nearly 200,000 units a year worldwide.
By markets and according to the estimates of the Japanese manufacturer, 50% of Insight sales will take place in the United States, while the remaining percentage will be shared between the Old Continent and Japan.
The commercial launch of the Insight is scheduled for the first months of the year, once it is presented to society in January in Valencia.
Compared to the first generation, the new Jazz grows in all its dimensions.
Its length rises to 3.90 meters (five more centimeters), the width to 1.69 meters (two more centimeters) and the wheelbase to 2.50 meters, which represents an increase of five centimeters.
The height, on the other hand, does not vary and remains at 1.52 meters.
Along with the increase in dimensions, the interior habitability also grows.
This gain is due, on the one hand, to the inclusion of a new platform and, on the other, to the introduction of the fuel tank in a central position, a solution also adopted in the previous Jazz.
Likewise, the boot capacity - which has a double bottom system - amounts to 399 liters, 19 liters more than the first generation boot capacity.
It should be noted that these measurements are from the version with the 1.4 engine, since the trunk capacity of the Honda Jazz 1.2 is 379 liters.
Other improvements - in addition to exterior elements such as rear leds or the possibility of mounting panoramic glass - is an improvement in access to the rear seats.
And it is that the doors that give access to the second row have an opening angle of 80 degrees, compared to 67 degrees of the first Jazz.
The engines in this second generation of the Jazz are also new.
At the beginning of its commercialization, this small model will have two gasoline engines of 1.2 and 1.4 liters.
Both mechanics incorporate i-VTEC technology that achieves lower consumption, emits less carbon dioxide, achieves excellent mechanical refinement and at the same time achieves high torque throughout the engine speed.
The first 1.2-liter mechanics gets a power of 90 horsepower at 6,000 revolutions with a maximum torque of 114 Nm. at 4,900 laps.
This engine - which in the previous Jazz reached 78 horsepower - has a cost of 5.3 liters and emissions of 125 grams of CO2.
Compared to the previous engine, which in the previous generation achieved 83 horsepower, now it has 100.
This 100-horsepower Jazz 1.4 achieves a combined consumption of 5.4 liters and 128 grams of CO2.
