The &#39;bee car&#39; that avoids collisions
To advance in the development of technologies for the prevention of accidents, Nissan has been inspired, this time, by nature, specifically, by bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, based on the flight of bees, prevents accidents.
This is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C which is the first step in collision avoidance technologies.
Engineers at the Nissan Motor Co. Advanced Technical Center have developed this small robot in collaboration with the Center for Advanced Science and Technology Research at the prestigious University of Tokyo in Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, General Manager of Public Relations for Technology and Brand Management R&amp;D, the BR23C is billed as an extension of Nissan&#39;s four-area Safety Shield.
This robot intends to reinforce the collision avoidance capacity of the brand&#39;s vehicles.
During its flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space that closely resembles the Nissan Security Shield.
But most important are the bee&#39;s compound eyes, capable of seeing at an angle of more than 300 degrees in all directions, allowing it to fly without interruption within its own personal space.
To recreate this visual feature, engineers designed what they called a Laser Range Finder.
It detects obstacles up to two meters away within a 180-degree radius in front of the BR23C, calculates the distance to the object, and sends a signal to an on-board microprocessor that immediately translates into preventing collision.
&quot;The moment it detects an obstacle, the little robot will imitate the movements of a bee and immediately change direction by turning its wheels at a right angle or greater to avoid collision.
The biggest difference with any existing system is that the evasion maneuver is totally instinctive.
Otherwise, the robot would not be able to react fast enough to avoid obstacles,&quot; explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and lead engineer on this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot be deflected up or down, nor diagonally; It can only move in two dimensions and in the direction that its wheels allow it to turn, and not in infinite directions and ways like bees.
For this reason, Nissan has used a rotation function, as well as acceleration and deceleration, to help the little robot avoid collisions.
&quot;This device only needs to process information every few seconds, and act on that data.
