talk sleep
Some children talk at night.
I am not referring to those who wake up very alert telling us something that happened the day before, but to children who talk while they are asleep.
The first time it happens you might get a scare, but it really doesn&#39;t matter.
It is a benign sleep disorder called somniloquy.
It is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
Surely more than one has been told that he spoke at night.
This phenomenon can appear very sporadically (once in a lifetime, for example, associated with an episode of high fever), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month...), the next day the child does not remember anything.
There is no single cause that determines its appearance.
They are often related to other sleep disturbances such as nightmares, night terrors, bedwetting (peeing while asleep) or sleepwalking, but it doesn&#39;t have to be that way.
As we have already mentioned above, they can also be associated with very high fever, stressful situations or overexcitation.
In any case, it is a little-studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it appears is also highly variable.
It may be that he speaks in a calm tone of voice, single words, a whisper or the opposite (shouting, crying, long speeches...).
In cases where the manifestation is very intense, it would be convenient to observe the child and consult a specialist, to check if there is any issue that is generating a lot of anxiety and gives him an outlet in this way.
We have said that it is a benign disorder, therefore it cannot be treated, unless it is associated with another sleep disorder that can be treated (for example, if it is associated with sleep apnea or a stress disorder).
What can be done is to take into account a series of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child too much before going to sleep.
Therefore look for quiet games and avoid programs or television series that are scary or a little violent.
With children who are very nervous and have a hard time relaxing, relaxation techniques can be used to help them gain some inner calm.
This will help the child to have a more peaceful sleep.
Once the somniloquias appear, try to remain calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day they will not remember anything that happened.
Helpful tips
Don&#39;t wake him up.
It is useless, because he is not conscious, and you will disturb his sleep.
Although he is talking, he is sleeping and therefore he is resting.
Remember that if he is very distressed during several episodes, it would be convenient to consult or find out what is causing so much anxiety in the child.
If what he says is understood (which is not the most common), do not be tempted to question him to extract information from him.
You will not achieve anything, because being asleep you are not conscious enough to organize your thoughts.
In addition, you will hear what he says, but you do not know what he is dreaming to say that, so be very careful in how you interpret the information and with the conclusions you draw.
Never tell the child that you can question him at night to find out his secrets.
Not even kidding.
That creates a lot of anxiety.
In short, don&#39;t worry, it&#39;s not bad at all, it&#39;s an episode that only lasts a few minutes.
