They all looked well upon their arrival at 3:30 p.m. aboard a special plane at the Al Maza military base, adjacent to Cairo International Airport.
They were immediately transported by helicopters to the hospital in Maadi, a residential suburb of Cairo, for medical tests, so they have not been able to speak to the press.
&quot;They are in good health&quot; and &quot;no ransom was paid&quot; to the kidnappers, Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garana said at the airport.
On September 19, these hostages fell into the hands of 35 unknown kidnappers while they were enjoying a jeep safari in a desert area at the foot of Mount Ouanat, on the borders of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, and have since moved from one hole to another.
The group was made up of eleven tourists -five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian- and eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the Aegyptous travel agency, in charge of organizing the safari.
An Egyptian security official said that 30 members of the special forces, transported aboard two helicopters, had launched the assault during the night before dawn.
&quot;An exchange of shots took place, and they killed half of the kidnappers, the rest have fled,&quot; said this official who remained anonymous.
According to him, 150 members of the Egyptian special forces of the &quot;lightning&quot; unit were sent to Sudan, where they were supported by German and Italian commandos.
Italian Foreign Minister Franco Frattini mentioned in Belgrade the role played by secret agents and by members of the Italian special forces.
&quot;It must be recognized that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of our men from the secret services, from the special forces,&quot; he declared without going into details.
He also denied paying a ransom.
The day before, the Sudanese army claimed to have intercepted a jeep carrying the kidnappers during a patrol, killing six of them, including the Chadian chief, and detaining two.
He also claimed that they were linked to a Darfur rebel group, the Sudan Liberation Movement-Unity, (SLA-U), a claim immediately denied by this group.
