The Interview - Blood Is Safe Again
Héma-Québec celebrated its 10th anniversary yesterday, and its president, Francine Décary, had reason to rejoice, because Héma-Québec has once again become one of the safest and most efficient blood providers in the world.
And above all, he regained the trust of the public that had been seriously shaken by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, the national blood pools managed by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Transfusion Service have been contaminated by the Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) and the hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
Faced with this drama and public discontent, the Canadian government conducted a public inquiry in February 1994, chaired by Judge Horacio Krever, which sought to clarify the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy and formulate recommendations so that such a disaster does not happen. play more.
While Judge Krever was slow to present his account, certain provinces then created a committee whose objective was to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau committee fulfilled this mission.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers have been created in Canada: Héma-Québec to supply Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and both territories.
&quot;In 1998, when Héma-Québec started its activities, almost 38% of the people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec, recalls Décary.
The situation was grim.
After having made many efforts to improve the safety of blood products and a lot of work in the years that followed, we have regained the trust of the public,&quot; he says before proudly stating that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of the Quebec population henceforth he had confidence in Héma-Québec.
Doctor Décary reminds, however, that &quot;trust is something extremely fragile&quot;.
Since its creation on September 28, 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, in Europe we were witnessing the birth of numerous cases of the human variant of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says Décary.
And we didn&#39;t know if this disease could be transmitted by blood.
So we rely on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports, according to which when we do not know and when a serious disease can emanate from it, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, we institute exclusion measures.
In April 1999, we refused blood from people who had stayed in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
But, a few years ago, it was proven beyond any doubt that this disease is transmitted by blood.
This episode thus showed us that the precautionary principle that was applied made sense. &quot;
In 1999, a much more sensitive HIV detection technique appeared on the market: nucleic acid tests that allow the presence of the virus to be detected directly in the blood of donors and not that of antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used so far.
Nucleic acid tests made it possible to shorten the period between the moment the person was infected and the moment the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
We were able to reduce this period to less than a week.
In this way, we substantially reduce the risk that certain donors are infected without knowing it and that we cannot detect them.
These improvements made it possible to considerably lower the risk of contracting AIDS from a blood transfusion.
Today, one person in 12 million is at risk of receiving HIV-contaminated blood.
&quot;That means 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
Thus, since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission by blood product occurs.
I believe that today you can receive or prescribe a blood transfusion to regain your health without worry,&quot; says the head of the Héma-Québec management.
&quot;Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know what pathogen might emerge in the system.
Last year, the Chikungunya virus appeared on Reunion Island, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
You have to be constantly vigilant &quot;, pursues Dr. Décary before stressing that in addition to a secure supply, Héma-Québec must also provide for a sufficient supply.
&quot;The needs increase because the population ages.
Because of the most aggressive anti-cancer treatments, patients often need an injection of red blood cells or platelets.
The aging of the population also has consequences on the network of blood donors which brings together on average only 3% of Quebecois eligible to donate blood. &quot;
All people in good health, 18 years of age and meeting the eligibility criteria can nevertheless donate blood every 56 days, that is, six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who propose their blood are not accepted, because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they traveled to a country where malaria reigns, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
&quot;With this 3%, we managed to maintain an inventory that covers the needs of hospitals.
Hardships are very rare.
But you have to renew the members of this donor network as they get older and can no longer donate their blood.
But it is difficult to convince people to donate their blood, but above all to retain them and encourage them to be a regular donor.
Since life today is very hectic, we rarely find the time to spend an hour to donate your blood &quot;, mourns Francine Décary.
With a budget of $297 million per year, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissue, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is almost exclusively used for major burns.
These tissues are analyzed, transformed and frozen before being stored at Hema-Québec, which also manages the only public umbilical cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord, which was once considered biomedical waste, is filled with blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases such as leukemia.
&quot; A few weeks ago we celebrated the bank of our thousandth umbilical cord blood sample and it is expected to take more than a thousand of these per year.
We should start proposing it for grafts at the beginning of next year&quot;, says Dr. Décary, who describes this cord blood collection program as very popular.
&quot;Many moms are disappointed that they can&#39;t take advantage of this,&quot; since Héma-Québec does not have the resources to offer this complex and expensive program in all Quebec hospitals.
