Free opinion - The Orwellian discourse of Barrick Gold
In its September 17 issue, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J . Garver, vice president and director of the Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
Following Orwellian logic, Barrick Gold claims that the world&#39;s largest gold company launched a six million euro libel suit against three authors and a small publishing house in order to provoke a &quot;transparent public debate.&quot;
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth that they judge, especially in the case of prosecutions for defamation, but the law.
Not surprisingly, this fundamental difference is completely hidden by Mr. Garver.
Why, according to Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate would be to harm anyone who dares to hold a position contrary to yours?
The outcome of the lawsuit is of little consequence, the authors and the publisher of the book Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums in order to prepare their defense and to fight, with very unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers supported by the almost bottomless pockets of the miner.
The tactic, in these lopsided fights, is often to bankrupt the defendants in order to impose an amicable settlement that will muzzle the opposition as well as scare off anyone who will dare to revisit the issue.
If Barrick Gold had truly wanted a public debate, it is in front of public opinion that it would have had to present its view of the facts.
Contrary to what is done in several of the countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada are usually done by exchanging ideas and not by blows of a club.
It was therefore enough for the mining company to open its books, its files and establish a true debate, through newspapers, the media, publications and the financing of independent search teams that could have clarified the issue.
But Barrick Gold appears to distrust public opinion and rejects petitions and letters of support for Noir Canada authors.
Possibly Mr. Garver could explain how you can ask for a &quot;public&quot; debate disregarding the latter&#39;s views?
According to the vice president, it seems that this word refers only to highly paid lawyers and not to all Canadians; that represents a very limited view of the concept.
In a democracy, detractors also have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold does not understand - or does not want to understand - is that the public that supports the authors and editors of Noir Canada does so above all because it rejects the mining company&#39;s brutal manner.
This public is willing to listen to Barrick and to judge it, but on the basis of civilized exchanges of arguments, and not in the framework of what many people perceive as a gag chase (in pursuit of &quot;public debate&quot;, Barrick Gold has just deposited a requirement regarding the authors of Noir Canada intimidating them not to use this word anymore).
In addition to Mr. Garver&#39;s surreal speech, the Barrick Gold trial is a direct attack on the freedom of university and truth-seeking essential to all democratic societies.
It denies the right to cite credible sources and to debate facts and interpretations, which represent the basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss subjects that are disliked by the rich companies of this world in a country like Canada, under pain of many persecutions, who will be able to do it?
If Barrick Gold truly wanted a transparent, public debate, it could do so by following the scientific standards used by the Noir Canada authors.
You have a right of reply.
The university world, to which we belong, has long known how to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold&#39;s excessive persecution clearly shows that, contrary to what it claims, it does not want to have a transparent debate.
It is a loss for the university world, but also for the public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place devices that limit this kind of abusive persecution.
Wall Street Bailout - Democrats and Republicans Agree
The Bush administration and the leaders of Congress, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the most important economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the 700 billion US dollar plan that aims to stop the financial crisis that has been shaking Wall Street for months has yet to be confirmed by both Houses of Congress.
In particular, it foresees: a better control by those elected of its implementation, of new mechanisms that aim to ensure the reimbursement of public money invested, of the new provisions to contain the number of foreclosed houses and non-payment, as well as a right of control over the salaries paid to the leaders of the supported companies.
The American Secretary of the Treasury, Henry Paulson, the Speaker of the House of Representatives, Nancy Pelosi, and the Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight, yesterday, at the end of of a marathon of negotiations that lasted two days.
&quot; We made great progress towards an agreement that will be effective in the markets &quot;, declared the representative of the Bush administration, Henry Paulson.
&quot;Everything has been done to cover the economy and ordinary Americans in the face of the current crisis on Wall Street,&quot; explained the Democrat.
&quot;It&#39;s the bottom line: If we don&#39;t do this, the trauma, the chaos and the disruption to the daily lives of Americans will be immense,&quot; said Republican Judd Gregg.
The negotiations had ended very quickly in the last hours because they feared the effect that a new failure would have on the mood of investors.
The latest time they had set was the opening of the markets this morning.
The two candidates in the American presidential elections, who joined the negotiations late, showed themselves rather favorable for the agreement, without forgetting, however, to express their discontent to be forced to reach this end.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama was given certain provisions to reach the agreement, particularly the one that would allow the owners to keep their domicile and the one on the salary of the managers of the surviving companies by the State.
&quot;When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of some, do not congratulate yourself.
