His Republican opponent, John McCain, when asked on another network if he would vote for the proposed plan, replied that: &quot;I would like to see the details, but I hope to vote on it.&quot;
&quot;The important points that I read [show] that it is something that we will have to digest and with which we will be able to advance.
He said the option to do nothing is not acceptable.&quot;
The 700 billion plan intends to buy doubtful debts, risky and unsaleable assets of American financial institutions with taxpayers&#39; money.
It comes after 14 months of a crisis caused by the bursting of a housing bubble that first led to the collapse of risky mortgage loans before spreading to other more common forms of credit titles (PCAA) and causing a liquidity freeze and a rout of banks and financial institutions.
It is a group of elected Republicans who had changed the first draft agreement, last week.
We believe we are out of the stalemate since the Democrats accepted that certain &quot;toxic&quot; assets of troubled companies are only insured by the government, rather than purchased.
To smooth things over for everyone in Congress, we also added a provision that if the government had to take losses for five years on this program, it could impose new rates that were meant to help it get money back.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first part of 250 billion to which another 100 billion may be added if the president deems it necessary.
Payment of another $350 billion would have to be confirmed by another vote in Congress.
In exchange for their help, Washington will obtain shares in the companies that have been rescued, which will earn them dividends in the event of profits and which they can sell again when the storm has passed.
The federal government will have the possibility of delaying the foreclosure procedures that concerned the houses obtained with real estate loans under this plan, as well as setting limits on the remuneration and on the cash compensation paid to the directors of the companies affected by the crisis.
The plan&#39;s architects would like to see it put to a vote in the House of Representatives starting today and in the Senate next Wednesday.
Despite all your efforts, you are still not sure that your plan will be approved.
Some people continued to protest against this bill yesterday, both from Republicans and Democrats.
Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House finance committee, told his constituents that &quot;by all accounts, Washington does not want to understand.&quot;
&quot;We have a very serious financial problem.
