What did the Zuschlag &amp; Co. invoice factory produce?
Very soon, on October 8, the criminal proceedings against János Zuschlag and his accomplices will begin.
The politician and his accomplices are accused of committing fraud of significant damage, in a business manner, continuously and in an organized manner, in addition to other crimes, including falsification of documents.
According to the Prosecutor&#39;s Office, they used the funds obtained in public tenders for their own purposes, justifying on many occasions the fulfillment of the tasks with false invoices.
The public funds and those of the municipalities - in their totality about 65 million HUF - stopped partly in the treasury of the organization Fiatal Baloldal and partly in the pocket of private individuals.
The method, which was also made known by the researchers, was to justify the collection of funds obtained in public tenders with false invoices behind which there was no real execution, the different associations never fulfilled their assumed obligations.
According to the prosecution, most of the invoices were false.
For this, they obtained the checkbooks in the market of the Józsefváros District and the circular stamps were manufactured in the city of Kiskunhalas.
And the question of which company the falsified invoice should be issued on behalf of was decided among others on that tour of the Upper Balaton Region where János Zuschlag sent István Lados.
The latter confessed that for this purpose he had to choose hostels and restaurants.
He requested an invoice for his consumption and these served as a model to prepare the invoices that they presented, among others, in the contests of the Ministry of Youth and Sports Affairs, in the Ministry of Social and Labor Affairs, as well as in the City Council of the Capital.
These invoices were mostly signed by István Lados and his accomplice András Őri, who according to our information rather wrote the necessary reports to obtain public subsidies.
During one of his &quot;field trips&quot; Sides chose a brewery.
According to two invoices issued in 2003 by Zuschlag and his accomplices, this gastronomic center provided food for a group of ninety people from the Biztos Pont Egyesület Association.
However - according to the manager of the center - so many people cannot fit in that place at the same time.
Similarly, the invoice issued in the summer of 2002 for the Jobb Jövőért Foundation - later renamed Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért - was full of formal and contextual errors.
Well, a hostel in the town of Badacsonytomaj had only three rooms and more than ten people could not stay there in one night, however the bill included one hundred and thirty people.
But the manufacturers of great fantasy bills also exaggerated when they pointed to the Pigal Kft gastronomic center, because in the bookkeeping of the same - according to the information given to the Prosecutor&#39;s Office - there were no documents in the name of Jobb Jövőért and Hoppá.
Győző Farkas, the manager of that company, told hvg.hu that when he was summoned by the prosecutor&#39;s office and they showed him the invoices, he already knew that they were false documents.
&quot;On the seal the name of our company and the NIF appeared in the wrong place.&quot;
He added: in addition to the formal problems, he also did not agree that according to the invoice, one hundred people stayed, since they only have eleven rooms that do not fit that many people.
In addition, meals were also included in the bill, while the restaurant has not been working for a long time.
The enthusiastic invoice makers were also not informed that the chosen travel agency in Budapest exclusively organizes trips abroad, so that on the invoice for cash payment they foolishly indicated a trip within Hungary as a service, which also did not coincide with the agency billing practice.
In addition - as it became known during the investigation - they included VAT in the document as well, despite the fact that trips outside the territory of the European Union were tax-free.
Among other things, the VAT measure was also incorrect in the four documents issued by the Hotel Révfülöp Kft. for the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, since the services of said company are not charged with 25 but only 15 percent VAT, In addition, the hotel employees only issued invoices made by machine, however the invoice was manual.
In addition, the &quot;shippers&quot; also made other mistakes, such as in the case of a company in which they included road transport as an activity on the invoice, which - it became known during the prosecution&#39;s investigations - is not carried out by the company founded as a consultant of investments.
Likewise, due to formal differences - inadequate format of the invoice, false stamp - it was learned that the invoices issued for Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, for XXI, are false. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and for Biztos Pont.
As in the case of Ravenna Bt. or the Kunfehértó Sports Camp, whose representatives denied having issued these invoices.
Neither did the counterfeiters pay attention to the fact that when the Fiatal Városért Egyesület group ate there (2001) the HIB Kft. of Nyíregyháza was in the process of liquidation, which is why the person in charge of the liquidation process - according to our information - denied having issued such a document.
They knowingly issued the invoices
Another group of manufacturers of false invoices are made up of those who were aware that they had to issue fictitious invoices.
The Esély Budapestért Alapítvány Foundation, at the request of Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták, issued an invoice for about four million HUF in the name of the Együtt Foundation to Harmadik Évezredért.
The manager of the Collab Kft. - according to the prosecution - was convinced by one of the defendants, Ludovic Györfi, to issue fictitious invoices.
In the same way, the Biogate Kft., currently undergoing liquidation, collaborated with Zuschlag and its accomplices, which in 2003 supplied invoices worth approximately 5 million HUF to the Jobb Jövőért Alapítvány foundation, the Atlasz Egyesület association and the Vörösfenyő association. Egyesület, with no real economic activity behind it.
There was no movement of capital either, since they later canceled the invoices prepared but forgot to record this entity in their documents.
The next group of fake invoice makers includes those who have some connection to the defendants.
Thus, for example, Iván Kubatov was the sued of the Ukrainian manager of Delta Trio SL with fictitious headquarters in Budapest, which dealt with the fuel and vehicle trade.
This company issued numerous invoices for an approximate value of HUF 18 million in the months of October, November and December 2005 for the sale of computer media.
According to the data of the investigation, these invoices were bought by Cash Investment Kft. of Kiskunhalas, which since September 14, 2005 is under liquidation process.
The manager of this company was a Romanian to whom Ivan Kubatov should have also sent the documents related to the company between 2002 and 2005.
We have information that Kubatov admitted during the investigation that he issued invoices for the Atlasz, for the Hoppá and for Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány in the name of the company, collecting the amount himself.
Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos-Investment Bt. were founded by Romanian masons at the express request of Ivan Kubatov.
However, none of the companies worked effectively because - according to the defendant - they did not receive work.
But he took advantage of these companies, since at the request of his accomplice the lawyer Zsolt Szente, who prepared the registration documents of the company, they issued invoices in the name of the companies for the organizations linked to Zuschlag: for the Atlasz and for the Y -Generation
Kubatov on behalf of Cash Investment, Delta Trio, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade gave a total of 15 invoices to different entities for a value of HUF 14.2 million.
The Prosecutor&#39;s Office considered that Kubatov received VAT and 10% of the amount of the invoices.
That man even took advantage of the Szi-Beri limited partnership to issue fictitious invoices used in the Biztos Pont contest.
The Y-Generáció and Szövetség a Modern Magyarországért presented a tender in January 2006 to Táncsics Mihály Alapítvány (TMA), a public utility entity of the Socialist Party.
From the contest they obtained 500 thousand HUF respectively, but they did not use the money for the purposes of the contest.
So that this is not discovered, they submitted to the TMA five fictitious invoices received from Works Team Kft.
These were the invoices found during the search of the office that Árpád Kemecsei had at the headquarters of the Ministry of Education.
Part of the defendants will probably recount in the trial - as they did in the Prosecutor&#39;s Office - the course of the falsification of the invoices.
The most interesting thing may be the confession of the main accused János Zuschlag himself, if he decides to dismantle everything.
Well, his confessions so far have not been very detailed and although he repeatedly promised to talk about everything, this has not been done until now.
The question is: what interest does he have in doing it? Perhaps in exchange for the return of most of the money - fifty million HUF - the socialists reached an agreement with him so that Zusi assumes all responsibilities.
Who, on the other hand, for these days could even be offended, since to alleviate his prison conditions he requested house arrest, but was repeatedly denied.
While the numerous perpetrators of economic crimes of much higher value, who never returned the money, walk freely or at least can wait in their own homes for the sentence, he has no chance for that.
Overlapping Psychology: Why do we spend more money?
Auction participants are likely to spend more money and overprice the product.
Neurologists and economists at New York University discovered the neurological-economic basis for this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to the study published in Science magazine, people do not want to lose in competitions such as eBay auctions, so they prefer to pay even an excessive price.
The scientists tried to establish the neurological scheme of this &quot;game&quot; by means of experimental auctions.
One of the groups of volunteers played the lottery, the other participated in an auction, and meanwhile, the active areas of the brain of the people participating in the experiment were examined using the functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) system.
In both games the participants could win money, but during the auctions, where it is a fundamental element to bet more than the other, losing the game intensified the functioning of the complex called the stratum located under the cerebral cortex.
This area of the brain, in addition to many other functions, plays a role in the &quot;self-reward&quot; mechanism of the nervous system.
Thus, according to scientists, the increase in bets is explained as a precaution so as not to provoke an intense reaction from the stratum.
To substantiate their theory, the economists in the scientific group also conducted a financial monitoring study.
In this experiment three groups bet against one person in different circumstances.
The control group was simply told the actual value of the commodity in question, and its members gambled.
Another group on top of that was promised that if they win, they would receive $15 more in prize money.
On the other hand, the third group received exactly 15 dollars before the auction, but in case of losing the auction, the members of the group lost even that money.
Thus, the only difference between the two groups was that success was highlighted for one and failure for the other.
However, testing the neurologists&#39; hypothesis, the members of the &quot;against failure&quot; group were willing to bet even more than the members of the control group and the &quot;winning&quot; group.
&quot;These results cannot be deduced from any previously existing economic theory.
Well, until now they explained the phenomena of auctions only with the joy of winning and with the prevention of risks.
Only visual neurological methods helped to resolve this contradiction between the two theories, so now we come to a third explanation&quot; - stated Andrew Schotter, a professor at the New York University School of Economics.
Hepatitis: When should you go to the doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary chronic liver disease is considered one of the leading causes of death.
The number of infected in this country is estimated at one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand receive treatment because many of the sick do not know they are infected.
Hepatitis is the common name for different liver diseases caused by viruses.
The symptoms are very similar; infection of the liver and jaundice are characteristic, but their pathogens and the diseases caused are very different.
Depending on the pathogen, hepatitis viruses are spread by two main ways: hepatitis A and E through food (for example with infected food or water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and fluids. bodily (sperm, vaginal fluid, saliva).
Travelers are recommended to protect themselves with a vaccine against viruses A and B, there are no vaccines against C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear two or three weeks after consuming the infected food, manifested by a poor general condition, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After that, jaundice appears on the skin and in the whites of the eyes, the stool becomes clear, the urine dark in color and the healing can last even two - three weeks.
Every year one million people die in the world from cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B, the most serious forms of this disease.
The main reason for this is that according to calculations, only one in ten infected receives drug treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: without treatment it can cause liver cirrhosis and even cancer.
Most of those infected do not know they are sick because this pathological agent gradually destroys liver cells and many times the first symptoms only appear 20-30 years later.
Therefore, early recognition and systematic medical control are very important.
This disease is much more frequent in three groups: people who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and those who wear tattoos.
Currently there are about 200 million people in the world who have chronic hepatitis C.
As this disease can be discovered with a routine laboratory control too, it is worth consulting with the family doctor when experiencing any unknown symptoms.
The disease is curable if it is discovered in time, it is possible to exterminate the virus from the organism, thus the contagion can be suppressed and cancer can be prevented.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, which was organized for the first time in 2004 by organizations representing patients.
Its aim is to draw attention to the causes of chronic liver infections caused by viruses and the importance of their early recognition.
The governments of the Netherlands nationalize a part of Fortis Bank.
The States of the Netherlands - being the first in Europe - will help with a nationalization of the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortis, which is in trouble due to the effect of the mortgage crisis on the North American market: the three countries will support a total of 11.2 thousand million euros to this financial and insurance institution that also does business in Hungary.
This weekend the governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands held consultations at the highest level with the president of the European Central Bank and the head of economic competition at the European Commission.
Fortis Bank is the first to suffer the crisis in the Euro zone in the framework of the international financial crisis that has been taking place in several waves for more than a year, therefore the decisions adopted with respect to the Bank, in a certain sense can considered as precedents.
According to the decision adopted in the early hours of Sunday, the three States will buy approximately half (49 percent) of the property that the Bank owns in their area.
The Bank will surely sell a part of its businesses, including above all the activities -mainly insurance- bought last year from the Dutch ABN Amró.
Fortis shares began a sharp decline last week and by the second half of the week there were already significant signs of crisis in the institution.
However, analysts agree that with its 85,000 employees, this Bank is too big to allow it to fail.
The company&#39;s shares on Friday alone fell 12 percent, the lowest point in 14 years.
Since January the value of the shares decreased by more than two thirds.
Looking at current share prices, the total value of the group&#39;s capital on the market is around 14 billion euros, but according to company executives this is not real.
The Bank&#39;s management attributed the sharp drop in Fortis shares to the insecurities of the North American market in relation to the approval of the American package plan of 700 billion dollars.
On Monday the shares already showed a slight increase.
On Friday they named Filip Dierckx as the bank&#39;s new CEO.
The Bank also sought individual investors, but so far no one has made a concrete offer.
The Belgian government had already previously ensured that investors did not have to worry, they will not lose their money.
Until now there has been no panic among the Bank&#39;s clients, they have not invaded bank offices to withdraw their money.
Fortis has its own branch in Hungary and has also bought leasing companies.
Does it hurt less who believe in God?
According to the result of a recent investigation, religious faith has a calming effect that also alleviates the death of the martyrs of Catholicism.
Scientists from the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experiment: they analyzed how religious belief influences human pain - reported the British newspaper Telegraph.
As part of this singular experiment, they applied an electric shock to 12 Catholic believers and the same number of atheists, while they were all looking at a painting of the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, the Catholic believers were able to exclude most of their pain.
Thanks to the human brain scanning technique, it was possible to verify that Catholic believers were able to activate that part of their brain that is responsible for pain regulation.
This experiment is the first of the series of investigations in which, along with academics, scientists, philosophers and theologians from different departments of the University also participate.
The analysis occurred as follows; a sparking instrument was attached to the patient&#39;s left hand, which applied the electric shock.
The researchers asked the experiment participants to fix their gaze on two paintings; the Virgin Mary, a work by Sassoferrato from the 17th century and the Lady with an Ermine by Leonardo da Vinci from the 15th century.
The researchers hoped that the spectacle of the Virgin Mary would provoke a certain religious mood among the faithful, while they chose Leonardo&#39;s oil painting because it was not too different from the other, and they thought it had a calming effect.
The patients spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, receiving in that period 20 electric shocks in four successive parts while looking at the religious or other theme painting.
The Catholics affirmed that when looking at the Virgin Mary they felt &quot;safe&quot; as &quot;protected&quot; people, &quot;they calmed down and peace reigned in their hearts.&quot;
When looking at the painting with a religious theme, they felt 12 percent less pain than when they looked at Leonardo&#39;s work.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the experiment, thinks that with any image so impressive a similar effect can be achieved with atheists as well, you just have to find the right image.
&quot;We should find a portrait of a person for whom they feel very positive, such as a mother or a father&quot; - said the psychologist.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the outcome of the inquiry.
&quot;The exercise of faith should and in many cases does change our personality,&quot; added Wright.
After these formidable results, only one question remains: what effect would it have on pain regulation if the Madonna by Leonardo or another painter of his stature were shown to the faithful?
Would the vision of a high-quality Virgin Mary yield even better results?
You are what you say about yourself
On its tenth birthday, Google can say: it can be found both in people&#39;s pockets and in the sky above their heads; he knows where they spent their holidays, which doctors they see and what interests them.
But according to Eric Schmidt, one of the company&#39;s executives, this is still not enough.
On the other hand, skeptics who make a parallel with the Orwellian vision do not see the essence of Web 2.0.
Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times newspaper that Google&#39;s main goal is to gather as much personal data about its users as possible, and this is necessary in order to fulfill the original goals of Google&#39;s founders: &quot;let&#39;s gather in one system all the information in the world!&quot;
According to the leader of Google, the company, even after ten years of work that has shaken the world, is still in the initial phase of the effort to be able to process all the information.
When asked what is going to happen in five years, Schmidt answered like this: I would like Google to be able to answer questions like &quot;What to do tomorrow?&quot; or &quot;What would be the best job for me?&quot; - However, the software will not be able to answer such apparently simple questions as long as there is not enough information from the users.
Not all Internet users are aware that while browsing the Internet, the keywords searched for, the IP addresses and the pages they went to at the end of the search are accurately stored.
Thanks, for example, to Personalized Search that debuted two years ago, users can store their own browsing history, they can go back to what they searched for before, what they opened, and thanks to this history, they will generate much more personalized searches -in this same logic will base the Recommendations, on which the system will offer us products and services based on previously defined and stored preferences.
What will happen if they use my data against me, if they collect information about my activities? - ask those users who worry about seeing Google&#39;s information monopoly.
In most cases it is rather the potential represented by the company that can be fearful and not remorse, fear of punishment, the yearning for freedom or rebellion against power.
However, it is a confirmed fact that they not only keep, but in justifiable cases they also transfer to third parties all the expressions sought, in these cases there is nothing that protects the personal rights of Internet users.
The most debated example in recent times was perhaps the coordinated action against Brazilian pedophiles, when Google provided the Brazilian government with information from its website, called Orkut, to identify pedophiles.
In contrast, Internet users who care about people&#39;s rights were relieved in May when the company together with the EFF, an organization for the defense of electronic rights, successfully proved in court that they were right in their lawsuit. with the FBI: according to the sentence, Google cannot be forced, through any of the points of the constitution, to provide any type of information secretly requested by the FBI.
(At the same time, the federal government managed to obtain, under the pretext of enforcing the child protection law passed years ago, about fifty thousand Web addresses and about a thousand search phrases, but without obtaining the search lists of individual users, nor neither are the complete lists of Web pages and keywords for the last two months.)
Thus, the opinion on Google is quite contradictory: it is criticized by those who are afraid to provide their personal data because they think that their privacy, their private life is harmed by starting to use Google services, and they rebel against it as against multinational companies of conservative image.
Meanwhile, the North American geek culture and its enthusiastic followers, Internet users and users from other countries, see in them the future generation, the &quot;vanguard corporation&quot;, not their rival, Microsoft, cataloged by its Windows as conqueror of the World. , no matter how much they both fight for the same goal.
This can happen because Google, unlike Microsoft, does not ask users for any identification code, nor money for its applications, the code is open and the free software package is constantly updated and seems more youthful, more collaborative than practice. from the official software giant.
But it may also be because geeks accurately see the highly problematic relationship between people&#39;s rights and the Internet that was produced precisely by one of the most mentioned keywords in recent years: Web 2.0.
Web 2.0 is about collaboration, about leaving intentional footprints behind us and taking advantage of available communication channels, and while the measures of these vary individually, the essence remains the same: showing ourselves.
A normal young person can have a profile on numerous collective pages, from Facebook to Xanga, and can even link them with other services, such as Twitter or last.fm that offers a list of their music habits, then they can be included in a follow-up system such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm, can also have a blog, in which the most recent photo galleries stored on Flickr or Picasa automatically appear.
We know of numerous cases from which it can be deduced that, for example, the girlfriend, upon seeing the flow of photos of mutual friends the next morning, finds out with whom her fraudulent boyfriend spent the night before or they can fire the employee of a company because he writes his candid opinion on the direction of the company on his blog: one thing is certain, the definition of private life has been completely revalued.
A person&#39;s online life is what he shows of himself - this is the definition behind the behavior of today&#39;s youth.
And anyone who wants to hide something, or at least wants to avoid Google&#39;s monopoly, can do so (starting, for example, with the Scroogle that uses Google&#39;s search system, but leaves no trace).
There are many people who do not want to register on the collective pages to avoid being found, but you can replace Google&#39;s &quot;online&quot; applications, from copywriting software to imaging and news reading applications with alternative versions which do not connect to gigantic servers or prepare the most perfect profile possible about us.
Public opinion almost openly awaits the day when Google shows its true face.
The company with its current value of 156 billion dollars is worth more than IBM (140 billion dollars), Intel (124 billion dollars) or Coca-Cola (110 billion dollars), the surfaces of AdWords/AdSense advertising threatens the revenue of advertising agencies, while increasingly rapidly introduced services cause serious headaches not only for Microsoft, but also for numerous other software developers.
Critical observers, however, will find the contradictions alarming as well: for example, top management flatly rejected employee protest after doubling the price of the company&#39;s day care center, considered unlimited employee meals too expensive, but All of this is nothing compared to the fact that in 2006 Google gave in to pressure from the Chinese government and the company according to the agreement leaked all information that violated good morals and the interests of the Chinese regime.
One of the internal regulations of the company says that they will not announce any new service in advance, but only when it is ready to work, what is certain is that the foreseeable problems of the coming months and years may turn the world upside down: while that some believe that Google&#39;s book and magazine scanning and archiving project will acquire such dimensions that the company will soon be summoned by the Supreme Court of the United States, others fear its Health system, because in it we can create our own health profile complete, with previous tests, with our doctors and our problems.
And the fact that Google is going to create a genetic database could provide good raw material for science fiction writers. Scroogled, the popular novel by Cory Doctorow, describes in an Orwellian way that future, in which a man alone from Google data can be described alarmingly well.
