The smart car imitates the flight of the bumblebee
What would be the best method for developing collision avoidance technologies, if not mimicking existing obstacle sensors in nature?
For example that of the bumblebees.
In an amazing project presented at CEATEC in Japan, the bumblebees provided the starting point for Nissan engineers to design the next generation of collision avoidance systems.
Nissan, in cooperation with the University of Tokyo, designed the nature-imitating BR23C-type robotic car steering system, which was given the characteristics of bumblebees, with the ultimate goal of creating a system that can avoid all collisions. .
During the flight, each bumblebee creates its own particular oval space that actually looks a lot like our protective safety capsule - explained Kazuhhiro Doi, RP technology director and research and development director, at the exhibition.
An important role is played by the compound eyes of bumblebees that are able to see in all directions at an angle greater than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of the compound eyes, the engineers used the laser beam length measurement system.
It identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C within a distance of 2 meters, at an angle of 180 degrees, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the vehicle&#39;s microprocessor which is immediately transformed into a collision avoidance maneuver.
In a fraction of seconds the obstacle is identified, then the robot of the vehicle, imitating the movements of the bumblebees, modifies the direction by turning the wheels as necessary.
Unlike any system currently in existence, this maneuver is entirely instinctive.
&quot;Otherwise, the vehicle robot would not be able to react fast enough to avoid obstacles,&quot; explains Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and vehicle robot project.
You must react immediately and instinctively, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable inner layer of the protective safety capsule, a layer within which all types of collisions are now considered inevitable.
The entire process should reflect what a bumblebee does to avoid other bumblebees.
This process should be done in the blink of an eye.
However, unlike bumblebees, the movement cannot be directed up, down or diagonally, but can only be two-dimensional and exclusively in the direction of rotation of the wheels.
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities that exist for bumblebees to avoid other bumblebees, here they only used rotational movement and acceleration as well as braking as a possibility for the car robot.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and have a higher energy density, which means they have a longer life than lithium-ion.
According to Andoh, what is important is the instinctive and intelligent reaction and not the processing capacity of the data, much less the storage.
This device only has to process a few input signals every second and react accordingly.
There is no need to store this data or react with instinctive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, thus using only a few tens of kilobytes of memory.
No gigabyte or megabyte memory needed.
This is the first step to develop the technology to immediately avoid obstacles, which according to Nissan calculations, within ten years can be incorporated into mass-produced models.
Another possibility for its application is to incorporate the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system to take the driver to his destination, avoiding obstacles in his way.
