fox in the chicken coop
In the United States, life and health insurance companies, upon seeing the data on drug purchases, often refuse to sign an insurance contract.
Privacy policy specialists fear that the personal data market will become uncontrollable.
&quot;There are programs for the protection of personal data, which binds the use of prescription data in all cases to the approval of the given person.
It must be in independent hands, because if not, &quot;we entrust the chicken coop to the fox&quot; - the Washington Post quotes Richard Dick, designer of the program for tracking medical prescriptions.
Insurance companies make the price of the insurance and the amount of compensation depend on the client&#39;s state of health and if they believe that the risk is excessive, they simply do not make the contract.
Before they sent the client to medical control and signed the contract with him knowing the result of the control.
Ten years ago Dick invented a much cheaper procedure: with the client&#39;s identification number he easily obtains from pharmacies the list of medicines purchased in the last year and a half and the program itself draws the conclusion about the illnesses and state of health of the patient. customer.
For example, if you consistently take large doses of cholesterol-lowering pills, it indicates that your blood fat level is almost incurably high, so you are immediately placed in a higher risk category.
Numerous versions of the program circulate, some even establish a risk number, so the insurance company as well as the administration hardly has anything to do, although there are small difficulties in this regard.
Among the disadvantages of the program is, for example, that some medications are multipurpose, for example, certain substances serve both to treat headaches and heat waves, and even as antidepressants.
The latter is an important risk factor for insurance companies while the former are not.
Special companies were set up to consult and process this data, which, before acquiring the necessary information from pharmacies, ask for the patient&#39;s approval.
The authorities already force them to do this, although they have not received a fine for their negligence up to now.
Some companies lately also prepare the results of laboratory tests and uniting them with data on drug consumption, they obtain more precise information on the patient&#39;s health status.
More and more companies have access to this data and simultaneously it is increasingly difficult to control its use.
There is an exclusive law for the protection of personal health data, but it applies only to insurance companies and those that provide health services.
The bill that grants the right to the authority to control specialized companies for the provision of personal data is already before Congress.
Dick Richard recognizes that this is insufficient: therefore he developed his program, which will require the specific approval of the person for the provision of their own personal data.
It is another matter that said person cannot deny his approval, because otherwise the insurance companies will not sign the contract with him.
So the chickens, despite everything, are exposed to the good will of the fox.
