Both in the United States and in Europe, for some time now the crisis seems to work as an accelerator for incubation phenomena that, with the new climate, solidify and come to light.
The first of these phenomena is the re-updating, the extraordinary reactivation, of the double category of state-sovereignty in relation to a type of re-nationalization of the economy.
The crisis, indeed, is a crisis of banking-financial institutions which have, yes, strong financial relations abroad, but above all, the balance sheets of families living in a single country and in a single state are compromised.
The one that immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: that is, how to respond to the difficulty and protests of those people and those families who, on the other hand, are voters.
The crisis appears economically global but is politically and exclusively national.
Political internationalism seems substantially out of the question or they don&#39;t have much to say: the crucial test is The European Union, which, divided as always between different interests and different state strategies, is unable to decide on any common policy.
It is from the government of each state that everyone expects an intervention, rescue and reactivation plans, new rules and above all the subsidy of funds: from the moment the cut is reached, it is only the state that has the economic resources and the mass of financial resources to remedy things.
And they also have the necessary means and the legitimacy to use them: two invaluable resources, values in certain circumstances in which no market probably and no organization will ever be able to dispose to the same extent.
This new emphasis that the crisis places on the nation-state is in perfect harmony, with the greatest importance whenever the new development of the economy tends to attribute it to a factor closely linked to that element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, while we were convinced that we had entered the network of ever more sophisticated technology, of the immaterial, while we were convinced that global finance was already destined to dominate the world, we realized that our future will instead have to do the math every day. once again with little immaterial things like water, crops and oil.
