Students victims of expensive rent, up to 900 euros for a room
The rental market for university students does not know the crisis.
According to the latest survey by Sunia, the tenants&#39; union, renting a single room could cost a student 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples, 600 in Rome.
&quot;The phenomenon has already taken on very serious characteristics to the point of excluding the right to study for a large part of young people due to the very high costs that the family would have to sustain – explains the head of the Sunia studies office, Laura Mariani – in these cities, strong demand has completely distorted the market to the point of unleashing a process of generalized increase even for residents&quot;.
Apart from the fact that in most cases the rental offers contain a series of violations: free type contracts, not registered, without limit of canon, linked sub-rentals.
For Sunia, extraordinary interventions are necessary that, through the revision of the tax rate, prices can be regulated.
Looking at the survey in detail, we see that in Milan, for a bed in the Brianza area, they serve approximately 450 euros; for a single room from a minimum of 650 (Bande Nere area) to an average value of 800 (Lambiate, Udine and Fiera area) to a maximum of 900 (in Victoria area).
In Florence a bed costs an average of 350/400 euros, a room approximately 700.
In Bologna, where students are concentrated in areas near the University, they serve 250/280 euros for a bed in a double room and 370 to 500 for a single.
In Rome, in the central areas near the University (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna) they ask you approximately 600 euros for a single room and 450 for a bed in a double room.
Only slightly lower values (550 euros for a single room) in areas close to other Universities (Ostiense and Cinecittà).
Savings are made only if the peripheral area is changed: 300 euros for a bed and 450 for a single room in the Prenestina area, Centocelle and surroundings.
In Naples you get 300/450 euros for a bed, for a room you spend from 400 to 600 euros, with the highest prices in the Policlinico, Vomero and Colli Aminei areas.
In Bari for a bed they serve you 250/350 euros, at least 350 for a single.
In smaller cities, prices are lower in absolute terms, but they have a greater weight in the city&#39;s economy.
In cities such as Perugia, where the phenomenon of renting to students and non-EU students is more frequent, there is a further anomaly: a 25/30% increase in the fee for foreign students compared to Italians.
Goodbye to the old Paradiso cinema, the cities cancel the historical rooms
The historic movie theaters close favoring the Multiplex.
&quot;A city without movie theaters in a blind city is like a face without eyes.&quot;
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore photographer with effectively what is happening in the great Italian urban centers and also in the provincial cities.
The process of marginalization of the cinemas, which with the birth of the great meticones in the periphery and the consequent disappearance of the mono-theaters in the central areas of the city, is an inevitable and indisputable event with all the characteristics of a true cultural crime. .
Historical places are almost always disappearing, full of memory, &quot;it is as if a friend died, an acquaintance with whom you shared a piece of the place and so much emotion&quot;, Observes the director of the new Paradiso cinema, the film that twenty years ago Back, cousin Oscar and the grand jury prize at Cannes won, which recounted the poetry of a provincial movie theater and the nostalgia for the way of living the cinema that perhaps lost forever.
The figures given by Anec, the main association of merchants, speak clearly: in the last five years 316 traditional cinemas have closed, and most of them are paying for the theaters in the main cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 less in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closures are first, Emilia-Romagna with 82 fewer cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
It is a demonstration that what is responsible for its disappearance is the agreement of the multiplex, it is these three Italian regions that have registered the largest number of new busy cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany than in Emilia-Romagna.
&quot;The Italian exercise has developed irrationally&quot; observes Paolo Protti, president of Anec, &quot;it would be useful to build new structures but it would be necessary to guarantee the permanence of those already existing, because when a city hall closes, not all its patrons are willing to be transferred to the meticones.
Not to mention the lack of funds in favor of the merchants: the previous debt of the state is approximately 10 million euros.
It is shameful from the ethical and moral point of view that the government does not respect the laws that exist.
To sustain the sector it would serve between 16 and 18 million euros a year.
The case of Bologna is interesting, the first Italian city that, concerned about the closures, decided to repair itself with the signing of a protocol between the municipality and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy to promote and protect single-screen cinema in the historic center than on the periphery.
Among the planned regulations there are fiscal facilitation measures in favor of managers and advantages for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the limited traffic area and will have special rates for parking.
&quot;It is an initiative that I like&quot; observes Giuseppe Tornatore &quot;and I hope that other cities follow Bologna&#39;s example by putting other measures in place.
It is true, that to contrast the extra power of the meticones, the traditional rooms have to improve the quality of the sound and the image because the public today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important to me: the closure of the cinema in Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make the &quot;New Cinema Paradiso&quot;, which I had been thinking about for a long time. 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass the Rialto or the Quirinale on Via Nazionale, already closed, where I have experienced so many shared emotions, so as not to see the billboards blackened by dust, I turn to the other side.
